              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>For Tenants:</strong> If you rent your home, you need written permission from your landlord to operate an STR. This is required even if you're in a two-unit dwelling.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>License Validity and Renewal</h3>
          <p>STR licenses in Brampton:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Expire on <strong>September 30th annually</strong></li>
            <li>Must be renewed before expiry to avoid late fees</li>
            <li>Late renewal within 60 days: subject to additional fees</li>
            <li>If lapsed more than 90 days: license is <strong>cancelled</strong> and you must reapply as new</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>How to Apply</h3>
          <p>Submit your completed application package to:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Email:</strong> licensing@brampton.ca</li>
            <li><strong>In Person:</strong> Licensing Administration Office, First Floor, Brampton City Hall (City Clerk's Office)</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="background-check">Background Check Requirements</h2>
          <p>Brampton requires a criminal record check for all STR license applicants:</p>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "A criminal record search conducted by the Police in whose jurisdiction the Applicant resides, or where the Applicant is a corporation or partnership then a criminal record search of all officers, directors or partners, confirming that there are no outstanding criminal charges or warrants pending before any courts, or any criminal record convictions within the last three (3) years."
            <cite>Brampton By-Law 165-2021, Section 14(6)</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <p>The background check must confirm:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>No outstanding criminal charges or warrants</li>
            <li>No criminal convictions within the past 3 years</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="insurance">Insurance Requirements</h2>
          <p>Brampton requires comprehensive liability insurance for all STR operators:</p>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "Every Person shall, before the issuance of a Licence to him or her, provide proof of Commercial General Liability insurance against all claims for personal injury including bodily injury resulting in death, and property damage with an inclusive limit of not less than Two Million Dollars ($2,000,000.00) per occurrence."
            <cite>Brampton By-Law 165-2021, Section 61(1)</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <div class="highlight-box">
            <h4>Insurance Requirements Summary</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Type:</strong> Commercial General Liability</li>
              <li><strong>Minimum Coverage:</strong> $2,000,000 per occurrence</li>
              <li><strong>Covers:</strong> Personal injury, bodily injury, death, and property damage</li>
              <li><strong>Ongoing:</strong> Must be maintained throughout license period</li>
              <li><strong>Notice:</strong> 10 days written notice to the city if policy is cancelled or changed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h2 id="compliance">Compliance Requirements</h2>
          <p>Once licensed, you must follow these ongoing requirements:</p>

          <h3>Display Your License</h3>
          <p>Your license must be posted in a conspicuous place clearly visible to renters.</p>

          <h3>Include License Number in Ads</h3>
          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "Every Short-Term Rental Host holding a Licence under this By-law shall include their Licence number in any advertisements soliciting Short-Term Rental Guests."
            <cite>Brampton By-Law 165-2021, Section 52</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <h3>Occupancy Limits</h3>
          <p>The bylaw sets strict occupancy standards:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Maximum 1 person per 14 sq metres (150 sq ft) of habitable floor area</li>
            <li>Minimum bedroom width: 1.83 metres (6 feet)</li>
            <li>Minimum bedroom size: 5.6 sq metres (60 sq ft) for one person</li>
            <li>For 2+ persons: at least 3.7 sq metres (40 sq ft) per person</li>
            <li>Children under 12 count as 0.5 persons</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Guest Information Package</h3>
          <p>You must provide every guest with a package containing:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>24-hour emergency contact information</li>
            <li>Floor plan with safety equipment locations and exits</li>
            <li>Police emergency and non-emergency contacts</li>
            <li>Nearest emergency medical services</li>
            <li>Waste disposal and property maintenance info</li>
            <li>Parking instructions</li>
            <li>Complaint procedures</li>
            <li>Fire safety plan and occupancy limit</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Record Keeping</h3>
          <p>You must keep records of each rental for <strong>6 years</strong> including:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Number of nights rented</li>
            <li>Nightly and total price charged</li>
            <li>Whether it was entire-unit or partial-unit rental</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="mat">Municipal Accommodation Tax (MAT)</h2>
          <p>Brampton collects a 4% Municipal Accommodation Tax on all short-term rentals.</p>

          <div class="highlight-box">
            <h4>4% MAT</h4>
            <p>The 4% tax applies to the rental price and must be collected from guests and remitted to the city. Major platforms like Airbnb typically collect and remit this automatically.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="official-resources">Official Resources</h2>
